post_text:
This afternoon, one of our CV families presented the CV school district with a donation from @lancastermasks, a nonprofit organization that produces and donates masks to Lancaster County communities and organizations. On behalf of the district, Superintendent Dr. Dave Zuilkoski accepted not only a monetary donation to use as needed to help keep students and staff safe during the pandemic, but also a case of hand sanitizer, produced by KO Industries in York, Pa.

Lancaster Masks is a 100% volunteer organization with all proceeds from the sale of masks going towards efforts to help Lancaster County open safely.

#cvstrong #lancastermasks #cvsd #lancaster #conestogavalley #stayhealthy #staysafe #koindustries #strongertogether

Due to the forecasted severe thunderstorms on Friday, May 29, and after consultation with local meteorologists, we have decided to move the Buckskin Farewell drive-through commencement program from Friday, May 29 to Sunday, May 31 from 1 to 3 p.m. This decision is being made for the safety of staff and students, and was made in collaboration with administration, local officials and the Class of 2020 officers. We wanted to make the call as early as possible to give families and staff time to rearrange their plans. The online virtual ceremony will be released as originally scheduled on May 29 at 7 p.m. on the district website. The procedures for the Buckskin Farewell will remain the same. See more:

https://www.conestogavalley.org/site/default.aspx?PageType=3&DomainID=8&ModuleInstanceID=2045&ViewID=6446EE88-D30C-497E-9316-3F8874B3E108&RenderLoc=0&FlexDataID=13750&PageID=9

post_text: Congratulations to CVHS student Yesenia Velázquez Roblero!
shared_text:
Latin American Alliance
May 20 at 10:38 PM ·

We are so excited to announce this years winners of the Spanish Literature Contest, Level III.

The incredible talent displayed through the writings of all the students that participated made this a very difficult decision for our team.

Thank you again for all of your hard work and to the teachers and professors who worked to make this another successful year for our Spanish Literature Program, GRACIS!!!

Here are the 2020 winners!!!

🥇1st Place - "Una familia de Guerreros" by Yesenia Velázquez Roblero, Conestoga Valley High School

🥈2nd Place - "El árbol Genealógico" by Gino Avila, J.P. McCaskey High School

🥉3rd Place - "Más que Sangre" by Carter Davis, Franklin & Marshall College

🌟Honorable Mention - "Las familias son como un equipo bueno" by Jadikel González-Rivera

See the image below with the list of the next group of point winners.

Stay tuned for when we announce the winners for Levels I and II and Level V and higher--short stories.

post_text:
CV School Social Workers Are Here to Help! COVID-19 has affected all of us in different ways, but our School Social Workers/Home and School Visitors, along with the other IU-13 Social Workers and Home School visitors want you to know that you don’t have to go through this alone! Even though our buildings are closed, Katie and Carla are still here to assist our families! They can provide assistance with housing resources, food and clothing bank referrals, applying for state assistance, work with the homeless population, along with any other needs that might arise. If you have fallen on hard times and would like assistance, you may reach them at:

Katie Reiff (Grades K-6): 717-394-0555 x6840 or katharine_reiff@conestogavalley.org

Carla DiClemente (Grades 7-12 and Spanish speaking families): 717-397-5231 x 1001 orcarla_diclemente@conestogavalley.org

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VAqAWvXCi-g&feature=emb_logo

post_text:
In order to reduce the risk of exposure and increase social distancing during meal distribution, CV food services will be distributing multiple meals in its grab and go bags moving forward. The Wednesday, April 1 meal bag will contain three breakfasts and three lunches to cover Wednesday, Thursday and Friday this week. There will be no pickup on Thursday, April 2 or Friday, April 3.

Meal bags are available for pick-up at Bridgeport Plaza (1643 Lincoln Highway East), as well as at Leola Elementary and CV High School from 11:30 a.m. to 1:30 p.m. on Wednesday, April 1. The Bridgeport Plaza location is accessible from both Route 340/Old Philadelphia Pike (enter between Little Caesar’s Pizza and Dollar General) and from Route 462/Lincoln Highway East. The grab and go meal station will be in the parking lot between the Wells Fargo Bank and Alice’s Diner. To maintain social distancing, we are asking that families hold up CV student IDs and signs to the car window in order to indicate how many students need meals as they pull up to the pickup location.

In order to reduce the risk of exposure and increase social distancing during meal distribution, CV food services will be distributing multiple meals in its grab and go bags beginning Monday, March 30. Monday’s meal bag will contain both breakfasts and lunches for Monday and Tuesday. The schedule for the rest of the week will be announced Tuesday evening.

Meal bags are available for pick-up at Bridgeport Plaza (1643 Lincoln Highway East), as well as at Leola Elementary and CV High School from 11:30 a.m. to 1:30 p.m. on Monday, March 30. The Bridgeport Plaza location is accessible from both Route 340/Old Philadelphia Pike (enter between Little Caesar’s Pizza and Dollar General) and from Route 462/Lincoln Highway East. The grab and go meal station will be in the parking lot between the Wells Fargo Bank and Alice’s Diner. Families must show a student ID for each meal.

We thank you for your patience as we implement these changes for the safety of both our students and staff.

post_text: Important information regarding the Weekend Blessings program from CVCCS.
shared_text:
CVCCS
March 14 at 2:59 PM ·

To ensure the children in our Weekend Blessings program continue to receive their bundles of food while school is closed, families are invited to pick them up at Conestoga Valley Christian Community Services at 2420 Gehman Lane, Lancaster, on Wednesday and Thursday between, 9 a.m. to 3 p.m.

Please follow the traffic pattern when you enter our site, and let the volunteers know that you are there to pick up your Weekend Blessings bundles for your children. You must be a current client of the program to receive the bundles.

If you have any questions, please call 717-208-3711 ext. 101.

Thank you!

post_text:
Ninth Grade Course Selection Night is Thursday, Feb. 27 at 7 p.m. in the CVHS Auditorium. All GHMS 8th grade parents and students are invited to this presentation on the 2020-2021 course selection process for CVHS and how incoming 9th graders develop their schedule. Subject Area Supervisors and school counselors will be on hand to review curriculum and answer specific questions for parents and students.

Course Selection Night is the first in a series of important transitions helping 8th grade students prepare for high school. We are looking forward to meeting the class of 2024 on Feb. 27!

post_text: Attention HS Parents: the high school will experiment with a new format for their second semester Parents Night on Feb. 6, running from 6:30 – 8:30 p.m. Please note the earlier time. Instead of following your child’s schedule, the HS will use an “open house” format that allows parents to visit the staff members of their choice throughout the evening. Another new feature will be special sessions facilitated by school counselors. One session will be an “early bird” presentation covering general information and other sessions will focus on grade-specific topics such as scheduling, career exploration and post-graduation planning.

post_text: The high school will experiment with a new format for their second semester Parents Night on Feb. 6, running from 6:30 – 8:30 p.m. Please note the earlier time. Instead of following your child’s schedule, the HS will use an “open house” format that allows parents to visit the staff members of their choice throughout the evening. Another new feature will be special sessions facilitated by school counselors. One session will be an “early bird” presentation covering general information and other sessions will focus on grade-specific topics such as scheduling, career exploration and post-graduation planning.

post_text:
Manheim Township High School and the Peyton Walker Foundation are partnering to provide FREE heart screenings for all students ages 12-19 on Saturday, February 22, 9:00am-3:00pm at the high school.

This screening is open to all children in the county.

Registration is required and each appointment will take about 45-60 minutes. Parents/guardians must be on-site during the appointment. The screening includes a vitals check, a heart murmur check and an electrocardiogram (EKG). Based on the results of these initial tests, students may be provided additional free onsite testing.

Register at https://www.peytonwalker.org/heartscreenings.html before February 15, 2020.

More information is at the flyer here: https://www.conestogavalley.org/site/handlers/filedownload.ashx?moduleinstanceid=140&dataid=12631&FileName=Peyton%20Walker%20Foundation%20Clinic_Flyer%202020_HR.pdf

post_text: Cold and flu season is in full swing, and we want to keep our students and staff as healthy as possible. As a reminder, students should stay home from school if they are sick until at least 24 hours after there is no longer a fever or signs of a fever without the use of fever-reducing medications. For more information on symptoms and treatment of influenza, please visit the CDC’s website at https://www.cdc.gov/flu/index.htm.

post_text: A beautiful letter written by one of our middle school students!
shared_text:
Mental Health America of Lancaster County
January 5 at 12:00 PM ·

SUNDAY MORNING LOVE LETTERS...from a middle school student.

Our recent Suicide Prevention Meeting inspired so many letters of encouragement, support and love. The instructions were "write a letter to a stranger" who may need encouragement.

In the age of electronic communication, it's amazing how powerful and impactful a hand-written letter can be.

The results were some amazing, hand-written messages that we hope touches your heart and lifts your spirits...as they were intended to do.

Enjoy this week's Sunday morning letter and look for one every Sunday this winter.

To learn more about The Love Letters project and how to write letters, please contact MHA at mha@mhalancaster.org or 717-397-7461.

This love letter was hand-written by a middle school student at Gerald G Hueskin Middle Schoo

December 20, 2019 at 5:03 PM ·

A BIG thank you goes out to Mrs. Dupuis's second grade class at Brownstown Elementary. Following Homeless Awareness Week, Mrs. Dupuis's class decided to collect items for each student who was experiencing homelessness at Brownstown. post_text: Brownstown Math Coach Mrs. Gingrich's son Christian came in today to talk to many of Mrs Hawkins’ LEAP students across the district about the Rubik’s Cube. He talked about how cubing helps with math, science, and engineering, and answered questions from the audience. Some of Christian's records include solving a 3 by 3 in 8 seconds and solving a 3 by 3 cube in 5 minutes blindfolded!

Conestoga Valley TSA members are once again holding their popular Holiday Light Show at the Middle School. Park your car “drive-in” style in the rear parking lot and enjoy 25 minutes of lights set to music.

All lights have been sequenced by TSA members at the middle and high school. The show runs snow, rain or shine! If the evening is nice, you can bring a chair and watch the show from your chair. Light concessions are available for purchase.

On Dec. 7, there will be a special holiday show that will kick off the program! There will be caroling with the select choir, beginning at 6 p.m. Santa will arrive to kick off the light show at 6:30 p.m., and be available for photos afterwards. Free s’mores and hot chocolate will be given to the first 100 children.

post_text: It was a big weekend for CVHS Cheerleading! Twelve of the cheerleaders participated in the Navy Extravaganza in Annapolis, Maryland on Saturday, Nov. 23, where they cheered with more than 500 cheerleaders and dancers from PA, MD, DE and VA during halftime! Additionally, four senior cheerleaders represented CVHS at the Varsity Spirit Spectacular at Walt Disney World’s Magic Kingdom this past weekend. The girls participated on Team Minner during the afternoon parade on Sunday, Nov. 24 with more than 800 cheerleaders and dancers from across the country.

Additionally, four senior cheerleaders represented CVHS at the Varsity Spirit Spectacular at Walt Disney World’s Magic Kingdom this past weekend. The girls participated on Team Minner during the afternoon parade on Sunday, Nov. 24 with more than 800 cheerleaders and dancers from across the country.

post_text:
This week is Homeless Awareness Week. Throughout our 6 school buildings, you will find a display of shoes. Each shoe represents a student in your building that has experienced homelessness this school year. Attached to each shoe you will see a sentence that finishes the prompt “if you would walk a day in my shoes you would know…”.

Homelessness at CV is real. Contact our school social workers, Carla DiClemente or Katie Reiff to see how you can make a difference.

post_text: On Monday, Lori Dupuis’s class at Brownstown had a special visitor for Veterans Day! Nate Grucelski, class of 2019, joined the Naval Academy after graduating from CV. He spent the last several months completing his training, and during that time he could not contact family or friends, aside from writing letters. Mrs. Dupuis’s class wrote him letters of encouragement and to thank him for his service on Sept. 11. Grucelski was so grateful for the letters and knowing that so many were thinking of him that he came back to Brownstown to thank the class personally, tell them about himself and the academy. He reminded them to do their school work, be disciplined, and remember that they can overcome anything if they work hard. This is the definition of #BuckPride!

post_text:
High school students in Ms. Mead and Mrs. Smecker's classes came together on Wednesday and Thursday to create animal pumpkins. Students in each class randomly picked numbers to be paired with a partner in the other class. They then worked together to pick a pumpkin and plan what pumpkin animal they wanted to make. They then provided a material list to the teachers.

…However, as is life, the materials they requested were not exactly what they received! Instead, students worked together to adapt and problem solve to create their animals. After they are finished with their designs, the entire school will vote for their favorite pumpkin to win a prize!

post_text: Conestoga Valley High School students Heather Roland and Alden Salmons have been named Commended Students in the 2020 National Merit Scholarship Program. About 34,000 Commended Students throughout the nation are being recognized for their exceptional academic promise. Commended Students placed among the top 50,000 scorers of more than 1.5 million students who entered the 2020 competition by taking the 2018 Preliminary SAT/National Merit Scholarship Qualifying Test (PSAT/NMSQT)

post_text: GHMS Principal Denis Quirk was chosen to take part in the Real Men Wear Pink campaign, as part of CV's ongoing partnership with Relay for Life and the American Cancer Society. Real Men Wear Pink gives men a leadership role in the fight against breast cancer. Real Men Wear Pink is a distinguished group of community leaders raising awareness and money for the American Cancer Society's breast cancer initiatives, including innovative research, patient services, and education around screenings and risk reduction. Participants will wear pink every day in October and compete to raise money through online fundraising and networking. To find out more about Mr. Quirk's campaign and how to donate, please click here: https://secure.acsevents.org/site/STR/RMWP/RMWPCY19NER?px=51571885&pg=personal&fr_id=94678

Real Men Wear Pink is a distinguished group of community leaders raising awareness and money for the American Cancer Society's breast cancer initiatives, including innovative research, patient services, and education around screenings and risk reduction. Participants will wear pink every day in October and compete to raise money through online fundraising and networking.
